#compdef tran
# =============================================================================
# tran — secure file transfer + send tool with rich TUI.  Sends arbitrary
#        files (single files, directories, multi-file batches) between any
#        two computers over the public internet via a pairing-code-based
#        end-to-end-encrypted relay protocol (PAKE — Password Authenticated
#        Key Exchange).  Inspired by magic-wormhole (the Python tool by
#        Brian Warner) but rewritten in Go with a much richer TUI:
#        in-terminal file picker (browse local directories, mark files for
#        transfer, see size/mtime), in-terminal progress display, peer-side
#        confirmation prompts.  The TUI is built on charmbracelet/bubbletea
#        + survey's interactive prompts; the CLI subcommand structure uses
#        cobra.  Targets developers / sysadmins who need ad-hoc file
#        transfer without setting up SFTP servers, rsync over SSH, or
#        relying on cloud storage middlemen.
#
# Author:  Abdo Farwan (abdfnx) — author of several Go TUI tools (tran,
#          quill, gosh, etc.); active in the charmbracelet ecosystem
# Source:  https://github.com/abdfnx/tran
# CLI:     cmd/tran/root.go (uses cobra for argv + AlecAivazis/survey/v2
#                            for interactive confirm/select prompts +
#                            charmbracelet/bubbletea for full TUI mode)
# Library: AlecAivazis/survey/v2
#          ("A golang library for building interactive and accessible
#           prompts with full support for POSIX terminals" — the
#           canonical Go interactive-prompt library, by Alec Aivazis)
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — 446+ stars on abdfnx/tran; ships as static binary
#          for Linux / macOS / Windows; cross-platform pairing protocol.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CLIMBS TO 37 (TIES RUST)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 37TH Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 36 to 37 documented libraries
# (AlecAivazis/survey/v2 via tran).  New leaderboard: Rust=37, Go=37
# (TWO-WAY TIE RESTORED at R518 solo-lead chased down), TypeScript-Node=36.
# Taxonomy now spans 258 cross-language CLI library variants across 62
# documented languages.
#
# This completion PARALLELS R518's _desk (Rust's dialoguer) — both R518 and
# this R519 document the CANONICAL INTERACTIVE-PROMPT library for their
# respective language ecosystems:
#   * R518: Rust → console-rs/dialoguer (the GRANDFATHER 2017 Rust prompts)
#   * R519: Go   → AlecAivazis/survey   (the GRANDFATHER 2018 Go prompts)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS AlecAivazis/survey AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 37TH GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# AlecAivazis/survey (https://github.com/AlecAivazis/survey, 4117+ stars)
# is **Alec Aivazis's "Golang library for building interactive and
# accessible prompts with full support for POSIX terminals"** — the
# CANONICAL Go interactive-prompt library, released in 2018.  Where R510
# cliclack-rust is a 2024 Clack-port and R514 inquire-rust is 2021-vintage
# and R518 dialoguer-rust is 2017-vintage, **survey is the Go-side
# equivalent of dialoguer** — the OLDEST and most-deployed Go interactive
# prompt library, used by cobra-cli, the gh CLI's internal helpers,
# brigade, Tauri tooling, and dozens of other major Go CLIs.
#
# survey is DISTINCT from every documented Go CLI library on FIVE specific
# axes:
#
#   1. INTERACTIVE-PROMPT-FIRST DESIGN (NOT AN ARGV PARSER) — survey is
#      the FIRST documented Go CLI library whose primary concern is
#      INTERACTIVE TUI PROMPTS rather than argv parsing.  Compare:
#         flag (stdlib):        argv parser
#         cobra:                argv parser + subcommand framework
#         urfave/cli:           argv parser + Action-callback framework
#         kingpin:              argv parser fluent builder
#         kong R465:            argv parser struct-tag
#         go-arg R475:          argv parser single MustParse
#         opts R479:            argv parser frictionless struct
#         mow.cli R470:         argv parser SPEC-string grammar
#         go-getoptions R483:   argv parser Perl Getopt::Long port
#         commando R487:        argv parser singleton + colon ns
#         mkideal/cli R491:     argv parser comma-aliases
#         clir R495:            argv parser explicit constructor
#         teris-io/cli R499:    argv parser With*-prefix fluent builder
#         jessevdk/go-flags R503:argv parser reflection on struct fields
#         akamensky/argparse R507:argv parser Python-argparse-faithful port
#         peterbourgon/ff R363: argv parser functional-options
#         peterbourgon/ff/v3/ffcli R431: argv parser + ffcli subcommands
#         rsc/getopt R511:      stdlib-flag overlay
#         flaggy (integrii):    argv parser pointer-bind imperative
#         google/subcommands R515: argv parser interface-based Command
#         survey (THIS):        INTERACTIVE TUI PROMPTS (no argv parser)
#      survey-based binaries always pair it with cobra/urfave for argv
#      parsing — tran uses cobra + survey, brigade uses urfave + survey,
#      etc.  **First documented Go CLI library whose primary concern is
#      INTERACTIVE-PROMPT UX rather than argv parsing.** Parallel to
#      Rust's dialoguer R518, cliclack R510, inquire R514.
#
#   2. `survey.AskOne(prompt, dest)` AS UNIVERSAL ENTRY POINT — survey's
#      core API is a SINGLE `AskOne` function that drives any prompt
#      type by passing it as the first argument and binding the result
#      to a destination pointer:
#         var name string
#         survey.AskOne(&survey.Input{
#             Message: "Your name?",
#             Default: "Anonymous",
#         }, &name)
#
#         var confirmed bool
#         survey.AskOne(&survey.Confirm{
#             Message: "Continue?",
#             Default: true,
#         }, &confirmed)
#
#         var color string
#         survey.AskOne(&survey.Select{
#             Message: "Choose a color",
#             Options: []string{"red", "blue", "green"},
#             Default: "blue",
#         }, &color)
#      The PROMPT IS A STRUCT VALUE; the destination is a typed pointer;
#      survey reflects on the pointer to figure out the prompt's
#      generic type.  Compare:
#        dialoguer R518 (Rust):   `Input::new().with_prompt().interact()`
#                                  — builder chain returning typed value
#        cliclack R510 (Rust):    `cliclack::text(msg).interact()?` —
#                                  function-call returning Result<T>
#        inquire R514 (Rust):     `Text::new("...").prompt()?` — builder
#                                  + interactional method
#        @clack/prompts (JS):     `await text({...})` — async function
#        survey (Go):             `survey.AskOne(&Prompt{}, &dest)` —
#                                  UNIVERSAL entry function that takes
#                                  any prompt type via struct + pointer
#                                  dest; reflection figures out the type.
#      survey's design is the **only one that uses runtime reflection
#      on the destination pointer** to determine prompt result type —
#      reflects Go's lack-of-generics-pre-1.18 era when survey was
#      designed.  Post-Go-1.18, survey hasn't switched to generics.
#
#   3. `survey.Ask(questions []*Question, dest interface{})` BATCH API —
#      survey ALSO supports asking a BATCH of related questions in
#      sequence, with the answers bound to fields of a struct via
#      reflection:
#         questions := []*survey.Question{
#             {Name: "name",     Prompt: &survey.Input{Message: "Name?"}},
#             {Name: "email",    Prompt: &survey.Input{Message: "Email?"},
#                                Validate: survey.Required},
#             {Name: "password", Prompt: &survey.Password{Message: "Pwd?"},
#                                Validate: survey.MinLength(8)},
#         }
#         var answers struct {
#             Name     string `survey:"name"`
#             Email    string `survey:"email"`
#             Password string `survey:"password"`
#         }
#         survey.Ask(questions, &answers)
#      The struct tag `survey:"name"` binds each question's name to a
#      destination field.  Compare:
#        dialoguer R518:   each prompt is a separate Rust call (no batch)
#        cliclack R510:    each prompt is a separate Rust call
#        @clack/prompts:   `group({...})` similar batched API with type-
#                          safe accumulator
#        inquire R514:     each prompt is separate
#        survey (Go):      `Ask(questions, &struct{Tag1, Tag2, ...})`
#                          BATCH api with struct-tag binding — UNIQUE
#                          among documented Go CLI libraries.
#
#   4. RICH PROMPT TYPE-SET (EIGHT TYPES) — survey ships eight prompt
#      types covering the full interactive-prompt spectrum:
#         Input         — single-line text
#         Multiline     — multi-line text (Ctrl-D to submit)
#         Password      — masked text
#         Confirm       — yes/no
#         Select        — single-pick from list
#         MultiSelect   — multi-pick from list
#         Editor        — opens $EDITOR on tempfile, returns content
#         Password
#      Plus a `Required`, `MinLength`, `MaxLength`, `MaxItems` set of
#      built-in validators (each implementing the `Validator` interface).
#      Compare:
#        dialoguer R518:   Input/Password/Confirm/Select/MultiSelect/
#                          Sort/FuzzySelect/Editor — eight types
#        cliclack R510:    text/password/confirm/select/multiselect/
#                          spinner/progress_bar/note — seven types
#        inquire R514:     Text/Password/Confirm/Select/MultiSelect/
#                          DateSelect/CustomType/Editor — eight types
#        @clack/prompts:   text/password/confirm/select/multiselect/
#                          groupMultiSelect/selectKey/spinner — eight
#        survey:           Input/Multiline/Password/Confirm/Select/
#                          MultiSelect/Editor — seven types (NO
#                          DateSelect, NO CustomType<T>, NO Sort, NO
#                          FuzzySelect — but HAS Multiline which others
#                          don't ship).
#      survey's coverage matches dialoguer's (both are 2017-2018 vintage
#      and share the "classic interactive prompt set").
#
#   5. POSIX-TERMINAL FOCUSED with explicit Windows-compat layer —
#      survey's tagline emphasizes "full support for POSIX terminals",
#      with a separate Windows-compat layer in `survey/v2/terminal`
#      that translates POSIX TTY operations to Windows Console API
#      equivalents.  Compare:
#        cliclack R510:    cross-platform via crossterm
#        dialoguer R518:   cross-platform via console-rs/console
#        @clack/prompts:   cross-platform via Node TTY
#        survey:           POSIX-FIRST with explicit Windows shim —
#                          reflects 2018-era Go's less-mature cross-
#                          platform TTY ecosystem (no crossterm
#                          equivalent existed in Go at the time).
#      survey's POSIX-first design influences its UX: terminal control
#      sequences are POSIX-style (ANSI escape codes), with Windows
#      Console mode translation done in a wrapper layer.
#
# Bonus: survey's `Validator` interface is a SIMPLE FUNCTION-TYPE:
#   type Validator func(ans interface{}) error
# That accepts the answer as `interface{}` (any Go type), validators
# type-assert the expected type and return error or nil.  Built-in
# validators (Required, MinLength(n), MaxLength(n), MaxItems(n)) all
# follow this signature.  Caller-defined validators just need to
# match the function signature.  No traits, no classes, no struct-
# tag declarations — just functions.  This is **the most idiomatic
# possible Go validator API** for the pre-generics era.
#
# THE AlecAivazis/survey/v2 API SURFACE (verbatim from upstream README)
#
#   import (
#       "github.com/AlecAivazis/survey/v2"
#   )
#
#   // Single prompt:
#   var name string
#   survey.AskOne(&survey.Input{
#       Message: "What is your name?",
#       Default: "Anonymous",
#       Help:    "Your name is required for the form",
#       Suggest: func(toComplete string) []string {
#           return []string{"Alice", "Bob", "Carol", "Dave"}
#       },
#   }, &name, survey.WithValidator(survey.Required))
#
#   // Confirm:
#   var confirmed bool
#   survey.AskOne(&survey.Confirm{Message: "Continue?", Default: true},
#                 &confirmed)
#
#   // Password:
#   var password string
#   survey.AskOne(&survey.Password{Message: "Master password:"}, &password,
#                 survey.WithValidator(survey.MinLength(8)))
#
#   // Select (single):
#   var color string
#   survey.AskOne(&survey.Select{
#       Message: "Choose a color",
#       Options: []string{"red", "blue", "green", "yellow"},
#       Default: "blue",
#       Description: func(value string, index int) string {
#           return strings.ToUpper(value)
#       },
#   }, &color)
#
#   // MultiSelect:
#   var colors []string
#   survey.AskOne(&survey.MultiSelect{
#       Message: "Which colors?",
#       Options: []string{"red", "blue", "green"},
#       Default: []string{"red"},
#   }, &colors, survey.WithValidator(survey.MaxItems(2)))
#
#   // Editor (opens $EDITOR):
#   var description string
#   survey.AskOne(&survey.Editor{
#       Message:       "Detailed description",
#       FileName:      "*.md",
#       Default:       "## Heading\n",
#       AppendDefault: true,
#       HideDefault:   true,
#   }, &description)
#
#   // Batch (BATCH api with struct-tag binding):
#   qs := []*survey.Question{
#       {Name: "name",  Prompt: &survey.Input{Message: "Name?"}, Validate: survey.Required},
#       {Name: "email", Prompt: &survey.Input{Message: "Email?"}},
#   }
#   var answers struct {
#       Name  string `survey:"name"`
#       Email string `survey:"email"`
#   }
#   survey.Ask(qs, &answers)
#
# Built-in validators (each `survey.Validator` function-type):
#   survey.Required                           non-empty
#   survey.MinLength(n)                       string len >= n
#   survey.MaxLength(n)                       string len <= n
#   survey.MaxItems(n)                        slice len <= n
#   survey.ComposeValidators(v1, v2, ...)     compose
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER GO CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * flag (stdlib)                — primitive base argv
#   * cobra                        — framework + codegen argv
#   * urfave/cli                   — struct-list declarative argv
#   * kingpin                      — fluent builder argv
#   * kong R465                    — struct-tag declarative argv
#   * go-arg R475                  — single MustParse(&struct) argv
#   * opts R479                    — frictionless struct argv
#   * mow.cli R470                 — SPEC-string grammar argv
#   * go-getoptions R483           — Perl Getopt::Long port argv
#   * commando R487                — singleton + colon ns argv
#   * mkideal/cli R491             — comma-aliases struct-tag argv
#   * clir R495                    — explicit constructor argv
#   * teris-io/cli R499            — With*-prefix fluent builder argv
#   * jessevdk/go-flags R503       — reflection on struct fields argv
#   * akamensky/argparse R507      — Python-argparse-faithful argv
#   * peterbourgon/ff R363/R431    — functional-options + ffcli argv
#   * rsc/getopt R511              — alias-overlay on stdlib flag argv
#   * flaggy (integrii)            — pointer-bind imperative argv
#   * google/subcommands R515      — interface-based Command argv
#   * survey (THIS)                — INTERACTIVE-TUI-PROMPT library
#                                    (AskOne + Ask batch APIs +
#                                    seven prompt types + struct-tag
#                                    answer binding + functional
#                                    Validator API + POSIX-first
#                                    cross-platform)
#
# survey occupies a UNIQUE NICHE — the **CANONICAL Go INTERACTIVE-PROMPT
# library**.  Where dialoguer R518 is the 2017 grandfather of Rust
# interactive prompts, survey is the 2018 grandfather of Go interactive
# prompts.  Of the documented prompt libraries:
#   - Rust:    dialoguer R518 (2017) → inquire R514 (2021) → cliclack R510 (2024)
#   - JS/TS:   inquirer.js (2012) → prompts (2018) → @clack/prompts R512 (2022)
#   - Go:      survey (2018) → newer alternatives (huh, promptui, but
#              survey remains canonical)
#
# REAL-WORLD AlecAivazis/survey USERS:
#
#   * cli/cli (GitHub CLI, gh) — uses survey internally for `gh repo create
#       --confirm`, `gh auth login` interactive flows
#   * brigadecore/brigade:brig (2409*) — Brigade event-driven Kubernetes
#       scripting; uses survey for confirmed-action prompts and continue-
#       fetching prompts
#   * crazy-max/diun (4684*) — Docker Image Update Notifier; uses survey
#       for interactive provider configuration
#   * create-go-app/cli (2758*) — Create Go App scaffolder; uses survey
#       for project template selection
#   * isacikgoz/gitin (1867*) — Git TUI; uses survey for branch/commit
#       interactive selection
#   * AlecAivazis/survey itself — comprehensive examples
#   * cli/cli's gh extensions ecosystem — many extensions use survey
#   * abdfnx/tran (THIS, 446*) — secure file transfer with TUI
#   * Many cobra-* scaffold-generators use survey for project setup
#   * kataras/iris-cli (124*) — Iris web framework CLI scaffolder
#
# survey's adoption pattern: **THE DEFAULT Go interactive-prompt library**
# for cobra/urfave-based CLIs.  When a Go CLI built on cobra needs
# interactive prompts, survey is the default choice.  Newer Go prompt
# libraries (charmbracelet/huh, manifoldco/promptui) compete with
# survey for newer projects, but survey remains the most-deployed
# choice — comparable to dialoguer's position in the Rust ecosystem.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# TRAN'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from cmd/tran/root.go)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   tran [SUBCOMMAND] [args...] [flags]
#
# When invoked without subcommand:
#   tran                          Opens the full bubbletea TUI with file
#                                  picker, transfer status, peer pairing
#                                  UI (uses survey for in-TUI confirms
#                                  and selects).
#
# Top-level flags (apply to all subcommands):
#   --start-dir <PATH>            Initial directory for the TUI file picker
#   -h, --help                    Show help (cobra built-in)
#       --version                 Show version (cobra built-in)
#
# Subcommands:
#   send <FILE|DIR>               Send a file or directory to a remote peer.
#                                  Generates a pairing code; share the code
#                                  out-of-band with the receiver.
#                                  Receiver runs `tran receive <code>`.
#                                  Survey prompts for confirmation if the
#                                  file size is large or if a previous
#                                  transfer is still pending.
#
#   receive <PASSWORD>            Receive a file from a remote sender using
#                                  the pairing code (PASSWORD) shared
#                                  out-of-band.  Survey prompts to confirm
#                                  the source filename + size before
#                                  download begins.
#
#   auth <SUBCOMMAND>             Authentication management:
#     auth login                  Interactive login via OAuth (survey
#                                  prompts for provider selection +
#                                  credentials)
#     auth logout                 Logout
#     auth status                 Show auth status
#
#   sync <SUBCOMMAND>             Config sync management:
#     sync start                  Start syncing the tran config to a
#                                  remote backup
#     sync stop                   Stop syncing
#     sync status                 Show sync status
#
#   config <SUBCOMMAND>           Local config management (read/write
#                                  ~/.config/tran/config.yaml)
#
#   completion <SHELL>            Generate shell completions (cobra
#                                  built-in: bash | zsh | fish | powershell)
#
#   version                       Print version + build date
#   help                          Show help
#
# Environment variables:
#   DEBUG=1                       Enable debug logging
#   NO_COLOR=1                    Disable color output (survey respects this)
#
# Configuration file:
#   ~/.config/tran/config.yaml    Per-user config (sync settings, default
#                                  start directory, mouse-wheel enabled,
#                                  default provider)
#
# Typical usage:
#   $ tran                                       # Full TUI mode
#   $ tran --start-dir ~/Documents               # TUI starting in Documents
#   $ tran send file.bin                         # Send a file
#   $ tran send /path/to/directory                # Send a directory
#   $ tran receive abc-def-ghi                   # Receive using code
#   $ tran auth login                            # OAuth login
#   $ tran sync start                            # Begin config sync
#   $ tran completion zsh > _tran                # Generate zsh completion
#
# Security model:
#   - End-to-end encryption via PAKE (Password-Authenticated Key Exchange)
#   - The pairing code is BOTH the auth token AND the encryption-key seed
#   - The relay server can see metadata (file size, peer IP) but NOT
#     content
#   - Pairing codes expire after ~5 minutes if unused
#
# Sister tools by Abdfnx:
#   gosh                          Cross-shell scripting tool (uses
#                                  survey + cobra)
#   quill                         Note-taking TUI (charmbracelet stack)
#
# =============================================================================

_tran() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    local -a subcommands auth_subs sync_subs

    subcommands=(
        'send:send a file or directory to a remote peer'
        'receive:receive a file from a remote sender using pairing code'
        'auth:authentication management'
        'sync:config sync management'
        'config:local config management'
        'completion:generate shell completions'
        'version:print version'
        'help:show help'
    )

    auth_subs=(
        'login:OAuth login (interactive)'
        'logout:logout'
        'status:show auth status'
    )

    sync_subs=(
        'start:start config sync'
        'stop:stop config sync'
        'status:show sync status'
    )

    _arguments -C \
        '--start-dir=[initial directory for TUI file picker]:dir:_directories' \
        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
        '--version[show version]' \
        '1: :->cmd' \
        '*::arg:->args' && ret=0

    case $state in
        (cmd)
            _describe -t commands 'tran command' subcommands && ret=0
            ;;
        (args)
            case $line[1] in
                (send)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '*:file or dir:_files' && ret=0
                    ;;
                (receive)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '*:pairing code:' && ret=0
                    ;;
                (auth)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '1: :->auth_sub' && ret=0
                    case $state in
                        (auth_sub)
                            _describe -t auth 'auth subcommand' auth_subs && ret=0
                            ;;
                    esac
                    ;;
                (sync)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '1: :->sync_sub' && ret=0
                    case $state in
                        (sync_sub)
                            _describe -t sync 'sync subcommand' sync_subs && ret=0
                            ;;
                    esac
                    ;;
                (completion)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '1:shell:(bash zsh fish powershell)' && ret=0
                    ;;
            esac
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_tran "$@"
